         <abstract>
            <p>Solutions to the congruences $(1 + a)^{p^n} \equiv 1 + a^{p^n} (\operatorname{mod} p^{n+2})$ and $(1 + s)^p \equiv 1 + s^p (\operatorname{mod} p^n)$ are discussed. Congruences of this type arise in the study of the first case of Fermat's Last Theorem. Solutions to these congruences always exist for primes $p \equiv 1 (\operatorname{mod} 6)$. They are derived from the existence of a primitive cube root of unity $(\operatorname{mod} p)$. Constructive techniques for finding numerical examples are presented. The results are obtained by examining the $p$-adic expansions of the $p$-adic $(p - 1)$st roots of unity.</p>
          </abstract>
